              h2 Presentation First Outing

              p
                img#mugshot.img-thumbnail.img-responsive(src='../images/birmingham-meetup-18062019.jpg', alt='Presentation First Outing', title='Presentation First Outing')
                | This Tuesday was the first formal outing of my ‚ÄúContinuous Learning Dilemma‚Äù presentation
                | and also my first Meetup event.

              p
                | The venue was The Old Joint Stock in the centre of Birmingham and I was lucky enough to get
                | a lift from colleagues both there and back. Sweet. Only had to carry my Lenovo
                | home-weight-lifting-kit a short distance and I managed to remember my rucksack too instead
                | of the usual chunky and heavy laptop bag.

              p
                | I was a bit nervous because my presentation could be perceived as telling people about a
                | problem they might not know they have yet. However, it was a good, all-round experience.
                | One I‚Äôd be happy to repeat.

              p
                | Around 60+ people of 115 registered for the event turned out in their own time after work
                | to attend. That‚Äôs enthusiasm to learn. Some were even prepared to stand as the room was full.
                | Free food and beer was at hand but I‚Äôm sure that wasn‚Äôt a factor. üòä

              p
                | Andy Burgin (@andyburgin), from Sky Betting &amp; Gaming, talked about DevOps Transformation
                | and was quite an act to follow. 30 minutes later it was all over. A few people were kind enough
                | to give me a thumbs-up when I asked how it went. I‚Äôm taking that as a green light to proceed
                | with further outings.

              h3 Unexpected Bonus

              p
                | Bumping into a former agile team member who recognised my name on the presenter list and
                | decided to come along was a bonus and it was good to catch up and hear about his successful
                | learning journey from Developer to Architect. I love to see potential in people realised.
                | Go Harshad!

